  <h1>What are Javascript Operators?</h1>
  <p align="middle">JavaScript Operators are used for various purposes, and there are different types of operators used in JavaScript.</p>
  <p align="middle">Arithmetic Operators
used for Arithmetic or simply, math. 
This includes the 4 basic mathematical operations of + - * / 
as well as including more uncommon ones such as:
 % for remainder 
++ for increment
 -- for decrement. 
** for exponentiation
</p>
  <p align="middle">Logical Operators
used for combining multiple conditions to each variable/values.
These Operators include: 
&& for an “and” condition.
| | for an “or” condition.
! for a “not” condition.
</p>
  <p align="middle">Assignment Operators
used for assigning values to a variable.
These include:
= for assigning a value
+= adding a value to a variable
-= subtracts a value to a variable
*= multiplies a variable
/= divides a variable
%= assigning a value to a variable
</p>
</div>

<button type="button" class="collapsible">EG 3 - 4  |  Who Watches These?</button>
<div class="content">
  <h2>What are Comparison and Logical Operators?</h2>
  <p align="middle">Comparison Operators -
In JavaScript, there are a number of comparison operators that you can use to evaluate whether given values are different or equal, as well as if a value is greater than or less than another.</p>
  <p align="middle">As the name suggests, they are operators that compare variables and letters.

For example, x > 3, y < 5

Comparison operators used:
== equal to
=== equal value or equal type
!= not equal
!== not equal value or not equal type
> greater than
< less than
>= greater than or equal to
<= less than or equal to
~  String Comparison
</p>
  <hr class="solid">
  <p align="middle">Logical Operators -
Used to apply logic in comparing two statements or values to 
    get an answer of whether it is true or false.</p><p align="middle">As an example, x == 3 and y == 1

The different Operators include:
&& as an “and” Operator.
| | as an “or” Operator.
! as a “not” Operator.

Thinking back to our previous EG, we have different JavaScript Operators, 
Let's see if we still remember them.

Comparing:
(x < 6 && y > 0)
 x is less than 3 AND y is greater than 0, this is true.

(x == 5 | | y != 1)
x is equal to 5 OR y is not equal to 1, this is false.

!(x == y)
  x is NOT equal to y, this is true.</p>
  
</div>
    
